content.content:
We extracted the following data from the included articles using the extraction methods described in the AMEE guideline (Sharma et al. 2015):

1. General information (e.g., author, title and publication year), participant characteristics (including demographics and sample size) and characteristics of the educational content (including topic and the context in which the topic is presented, e.g. digital or analogue and type of study or profession);
2. Intervention (type of game element(s) and game attributes used);
3. Study outcomes (including satisfaction, attitudes, perceptions, opinions, knowledge, behaviour and patient outcomes);
4. Study quality (see below);
5. Theoretical frameworks used to design or evaluate gamifed educational programs.

We used the Medical Education Research Study Quality Instrument (MERSQI) to measure the methodological quality of the selected studies (Reed et al. 2007). MERSQI is designed for measuring the quality of experimental, quasi-experimental and observational studies and consists of ten items covering six domains (study design, sampling, type of data, validity of evaluation instrument, data analysis, and outcomes). The maximum score for each domain is three. Five domains have a minimum score of one, resulting in a range of 5–18 points. We calculated individual total MERSQI scores, mean scores and standard deviations.

To provide a clear overview of the current state of studies on gamifcation in health sciences education, we used the framework for classifying the purposes of research in medical education proposed by Cook et  al. (2008). They distinguished studies as focusing on description, justifcation and clarifcation. Description studies make no comparison, focus on observation and describe what was done. Justifcation studies make comparisons between interventions, generally lack or do not present a conceptual framework or a predictive model and describe whether the new intervention worked. Clarifcation studies apply a theoretical framework to understand and possibly explain the processes underlying the observed efects, describe why and how interventions (i.e. gamifcation) work and illuminate paths of future directions (Cook et al. 2008).

We classifed all included studies as descriptive, justifcation or clarifcation.
